title: For Sale:  Local, Legit - Buy an 80% receiver, the tools to finish the receiver, and I will buy the tools back.
postcontent:
This ad keeps getting flagged. I suspect the motivation for that has nothing to do with the rules of Armslist (and everything to do with trying to prevent others from learning how to simply and legally build their own AR-15 lower). 

In case there is some legit concern - this isn't some multi-state listing. I am local to ABQ, the Mayor's name is Berry and the Republicans just took control of the State House of Representatives for the first time since 1953. 

Here's what I am offering: an unfinished AR-15 receiver. The price is $100. That's a little higher than you can find online. But, you can buy it, locally, in cash and avoid the paper trail. Part of the point of finishing your own firearm is to avoid what many people believe are unconstitutional lists identifying gun ownership. It also prevents gun grabbing by the "authorities." Think that doesn't happen? http://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/08/national/nationalspecial/08cnd-storm.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0

But, I am also selling the carbide drill bits and endmills you need to complete the receiver. All bits/mills purchased from https://www.mscdirect.com/ as recommended by CNCguns.com - and one more part: the steel jig that you need to make everything line up properly. The whole package costs $375. I will buy the tools and the jig back for $275 (assuming normal use and not abuse). I am not renting the tools, if you want to keep them then they are yours. If you want to sell them back, cool. BE WARY of anyone who offers to "rent" tools to make a firearm. The ATF has decided they will prosecute people for that. http://www.atf.gov/sites/default/files/assets/Firearms/FirearmsIndustry/atf-ruling-2015-1-manufacturing-and-gunsmithing.pdf

It is legal to make your own firearm (as long as it is for yourself and you aren't prohibited from having a gun and you aren't making it with the intent to transfer it). http://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2014/03/26/80-ar-15-receiver-determination-letter-atf/ It isn't all that difficult: http://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2013/05/02/billet-rifle-systems-80-receiver-part/ 

If you don't think people should be able to build their own firearms, great: you are entitled to your opinion. But, this ad isn't spam, it isn't violating any rules of armslist, and maybe you should let everyone make up their own mind about whether this is something that they want to buy? Just a thought. As for the individual who emailed the rant about unserialized guns-- actually, I am a democrat. I just believe in the rights afforded to everyone by the Bill of Rights. INCLUDING the Second Amendment. 

Price is $375. Tools are $275 and Unfinished Receiver is $100. I buy the tools back as long as you didn't abuse them (if you want).

title: For Sale:  Buffalo Bore Ammo - 380 Auto Standard Pressure Ammo 100 gr. Hardcast FN (975 fps/M.E. 211 ft. lbs.) - 20 Round Box
postcontent:
https://www.extreme-impact-ammo.com/index.php?l=product_detail&p=216










Buffalo Bore Ammo - 380 Auto Standard Pressure Ammo 100 gr. Hardcast FN (975 fps/M.E. 211 ft. lbs.) - 20 Round Box













The 380 auto inhabits a valuable and useful place in our society, mostly because of the easily concealable, tiny pistols chambered for it. HOWEVER, because of the very limited size of the cartridge, it is plagued with limited power and therefore most of the existing ammo in 380 auto suffers from not being reliable as a man-stopper. We've studied and played with nearly all of the existing available 380 ammo and find it wanting as a reliable means of self defense, especially against a large, insane, drugged up/pain free, determined attacker.

Here's the problem. The current 380 auto frangible ammo delivers a large amount of surface trauma, but lacks serious penetration. For example, if you shot me or another sane man in the face with modern frangible 380 ammo, it would blow off a big portion of my cheek and send a few teeth down my throat, I would undoubtedly fall to the ground in shock and pain, but I would be very much alive and functional if I could get past the shock and pain as that frangible bullet would have stopped some where inside my face, never making it to my brain. However, if you shot a drugged up maniac in the face with that same frangible 380 ammo and blew half his cheek off, he would keep right on coming because he is insane and is not thinking like you or I. Plus, he is likely pain free and fear free and wont know that half his cheek is missing and if he did know, he would not care. So whatever 380 ammo you shoot him in the face with, had better go through his face and blow his brain stem out the back of his head, because only a CNS (central nervous system) hit with a 380 is going to stop him. Likewise, a torso hit to the sternum needs to penetrate deep enough to blow all the way through his spine in order to shut him down spontaneously. If you fail to shut him down instantly, you and your loved ones are going to have to find a way to survive while you wait for him to bleed out and pass out. The best chance of survival for you and your family is to shut down the attacker instantly. So, we've designed a few 380 auto standard pressure loads to keep you and your loved ones alive under the worst of scenarios.

Item 27E/20 is a 100gr. HARD cast bullet with a flat nose. It is traveling over 1,000 fps out of my 3.75 inch BDA (Browning Double Action). We've used a flash suppressed powder for all three of our 380 auto loads so that you wont be blinded by your own gunfire if you have to shoot in the dark and since around 95% of all civilian shootings in America occur in low light, the chances that your own gunfire will blind you while you are trying to save your life, are good - we've eliminated this variable by using flash suppressed powder. We've also chosen a flat nosed solid bullet. The flat on the nose ensures that the bullet will cut/smash its way through flesh and bone and do much more destruction than typical round nose FMJ bullets. Round nosed bullets tend to slip and slide through matter, doing little damage as opposed to a flat nosed bullet. The flat nose not only wounds much more than a round nosed bullet, but it actually keeps the penetration straight and thus deeper. Notice the below velocities recorded from my personal 380 auto pistols. These are real world guns and thus the speeds are realistic and not exaggerated speeds produced from laboratory test barrels. What you see with Buffalo Bore Ammo, is truly what you get in the "real world", where it matters. You can expect 20+ inches of straight-line penetration in flesh and bone with this load. If you are worried about over penetration with this load, DON'T! You chose to carry a tiny under-powered 380 auto pistol and the trade-off is that you are now going to have to stay alive with that pistol and over penetration will be the least of your worries if you end up needing this gun to save yourself or your family.

1. 1011 fps - BDA-3.75 inch barrel
2.   995 fps - Walther PPK-3.5 inch barrel
3.   910 fps - Colt Mustang Pocket Lite-2.75 inch barrel
4.   902 fps - Keltec

title: For Sale:  Firestar M43 9mm Compact 1911 Style Carry Pistol: Case & 2 mags, Galco Leather Holster, 50rnds
postcontent:
Not abused, runs without complaint, blue is looking not too shabby, please take a look.
 It's design is sturdy, accurate, and reliable, as I'll explain further down.
I'm just looking at other things at the moment, so I'm parting with this steal of a concealed carry package.

FOR SALE ONLY, accepting gift cards as well.
More pictures: http://postimg.org/gallery/2g56cljv0/

Before I dive in, if you're not familiar with this brand (like I was), you can dig around the web to find that they are a Reputable manufacturer from Spain.
Their .45 caliber pistols are highly praised (The two 1911's carried by Samuel Jackson and John Travolta in Pulp Fiction are actually Star 1911 Clones), and the other bored models are made to the same standard.




This is the M43 Compact pistol, available in 9mm/.40SW/.45.
Mine is the single stack 9mm, 7 rounds +1, included is a spare mag.
It's an "all steel" gun, with an inside the frame slide, this combo makes it an accurate little automatic. The heft absorbs recoil, and from what I've read, will stand up to 9mm + P ammo. 
>>Very quick repeated shots with this overall setup, the grip, slide/body, and trigger.
The LOCKUP is tight, and the BORE is in good shape:
The RIFLING edges are pronounced, has a shine to it still, I don't think it has been used extensively.

It's single action only and can be carried in either:
CONDITION 1 (round in the chamber with the hammer cocked and the safety on), 
OR
 with a round cambered and the hammer released to a half cock. When the hammer is down, the safety will lock the slide in place.

The TRIGGER is in a nice middle ground between the very stiff and very light.
On one hand it is just at the point that it takes a deliberate finger pull to fire,
 and on the other hand: the trigger reset is short and it has an almost two-stage feel.
 When pulled back, it comes to a tangible rest just before the break.
>>Very quick repeated shots with this overall setup, the grip, slide/body, and trigger.

AMBIDEXTROUS SAFETY, just like on a 1911. The beaver tail grip and indent under the trigger guard give you a surprisingly solid GRIP on the gun. If you have *big* hands, you'll probably dangle a pinky.



Included is the original Star FireStar CARRYING CASE,
 a SPARE MAGAZINE stainless 7 round,
 a Galco Leather Inside the Waistband IWB Locking HOLSTER,
 and ONE BOX of econo-target range AMMO I have leftover.

I have found a great web page for this gun, and have a PDF copy of the original MANUAL, I'll have that printed out for you.

This gun needs to be kept clean and lubricated to work properly, and it prefers quality ammo due to it's stiff recoil spring. The hotter, the better.




I'm asking $310 for the lot, I can meet anywhere public, I'd prefer to meet at a Police station (they won't be involved in the sale, however they don't mind for our safety).
Bill of sale with documentation of the Serial #, our DL #'s and FOID card if applicable.

If you wish to send a message, please email me.
I can be reached by phone at 2One 97 Nin e87Sev en 4 8,
-Tom
